abstract={Recently, educational games are gaining increasing attention from researchers and practitioners in the learning field. This is because they are fun, motivating and immersive. However, designing educational games can be difficult for people who do not have appropriate background towards game development. This is further complicated by the fact that there are many genres of games (role playing, action, puzzle, etc.) and each genre has its own game elements and functionalities. This makes the game design process confusing, especially for beginners. This paper deploys the powerful graphical representation of Unified Modeling Language class diagram to present a generic model of educational role playing games. This model uses knowledge representation (game elements, functionalities and features) to support designing educational role playing games. Fifty eight game developers participated in evaluating the model and they have revealed its high perceived usefulness while designing educational role playing games. In addition, they reported that they were willing to use this model again in the future in their context.},
